M|framing-analysis|name: framing-analysis
M|framing-analysis|description: Kahneman's systematic framing effect detection protocol. Covers gain vs. loss framing audit, reference point manipulation, choice architecture rv, and specific reframes. Used before any c
M|framing-analysis|version: 1.0.0
M|framing-analysis|The framing effect is one of the most reliably exploited cognitive biases — and one of the easiest to accidentally weaponize against the very customer you're trying to serve. This skill gives Kahneman
M|framing-analysis|- Any copy from Lena that uses "only", "limited", "last chance", "don't miss", "lose"
M|framing-analysis|- Any financial projection from Felix that leads with the positive scenario
M|framing-analysis|- Any A/B test recommendation from Rio or Nate that frames one variant in terms of gain and the other in terms of loss
M|framing-analysis|- Any strategic brief from Marcus that selectively frames risks vs. opportunities
M|framing-analysis|- Any request containing "framing check" or "@kahneman framing"
M|framing-analysis|For any cnt, recommendation, or dec:
M|framing-analysis|Is the same outcome described in both positive (gain) and negative (loss) terms before a recommendation is made?
M|framing-analysis|```
M|framing-analysis|Gain frame:  "85% of customers keep their purchase"
M|framing-analysis|Loss frame:  "15% of customers return"
M|framing-analysis|→ Functionally identical. If the recommendation changes based on framing, the dec is biased.
M|framing-analysis|→ Audit question: does this recommendation hold if framed the opposite way?
M|framing-analysis|```
M|framing-analysis|**Correction rule:** Any recommendation that is not robust to its inverse framing should be flagged 🔴.
M|framing-analysis|What reference point is being used, and is it the most honest one?
M|framing-analysis|```
M|framing-analysis|Problematic: "Revenue up 12% vs last month" (seasonal low comparison)
M|framing-analysis|Honest:      "Revenue up 12% MoM — down 8% vs same period last year"
M|framing-analysis|```
M|framing-analysis|**Audit question:** Has the comparison reference been chosen to make the data look better than a neutral baseline would?
M|framing-analysis|Is scarcity language ("only 3 left", "ending tonight") backed by a real constraint?
M|framing-analysis|```
M|framing-analysis|Real constraint: Inventory count is genuinely limited → permitted
M|framing-analysis|Manufactured constraint: "Only available until midnight" when midnight resets → 🔴 Trust debt
M|framing-analysis|```
M|framing-analysis|**Audit question:** If a customer discovered the scarcity was not real, would they feel deceived?
M|framing-analysis|What happens if the customer does nothing? Is the default option genuinely the best option for the customer, or for revenue?
M|framing-analysis|```
M|framing-analysis|Pre-checked upsell at checkout → examine who benefits from the default
M|framing-analysis|Default to annual billing → is this disclosed clearly before the "start trial" click?
M|framing-analysis|```
M|framing-analysis|**Audit question:** Does the default option require the customer to take an action to avoid an undesired outcome?
M|framing-analysis|Is negative information as salient as positive information in the output?
M|framing-analysis|```
M|framing-analysis|Red flag: 4 bullet points of benefits, 1 footnote of risks
M|framing-analysis|Red flag: ROI projection in headline, CAC risk in footnote
M|framing-analysis|```
M|framing-analysis|**Audit question:** If risks and benefits were equally prominent, would the recommendation still be made?
M|framing-analysis|Does a financial model lead with a scenario that anchors subsequent expectations upward?
M|framing-analysis|```
M|framing-analysis|Red flag: "Best case: £200k revenue" presented before "Base case: £110k"
M|framing-analysis|Correction: Always present base case first. Anchors set by best case inflate expectations.
M|framing-analysis|```
M|framing-analysis|**Audit question:** Would presenting the base case first change the risk appetite behind the dec?
M|framing-analysis|```
M|framing-analysis|FRAMING ANALYSIS — [agt audited] — [cnt type]
M|framing-analysis|POINT 1 (Gain/Loss):   [CLEAN | DISTORTED] — [finding if distorted]
M|framing-analysis|POINT 2 (Reference):   [CLEAN | DISTORTED] — [finding if distorted]
M|framing-analysis|POINT 3 (Scarcity):    [CLEAN | N/A | DISTORTED] — [finding if distorted]
M|framing-analysis|POINT 4 (Default):     [CLEAN | N/A | DISTORTED] — [finding if distorted]
M|framing-analysis|POINT 5 (Salience):    [CLEAN | DISTORTED] — [finding if distorted]
M|framing-analysis|POINT 6 (Anchoring):   [CLEAN | N/A | DISTORTED] — [finding if distorted]
M|framing-analysis|CORRECTIONS:
M|framing-analysis|[Point n] — [exact reframe, not "consider revising"]
M|framing-analysis|VERDICT: 🟢 Clean / 🟡 Caution / 🔴 Block
M|framing-analysis|```
M|framing-analysis|🔴 Block conditions: any Point 3 real-vs-manufactured scarcity failure, any Point 6 anchor that changes a budget dec, Point 5 asymmetry on a high-stakes financial model.
M|framing-analysis|- Never audit only the headline — framing distortions hide in footnotes, defaults, and comparison baselines
M|framing-analysis|- Never issue 🟢 with an unresolved distortion because "it's minor" — name it 🟡 and note it explicitly
M|framing-analysis|- Never confuse persuasion (acceptable) with deception (not acceptable) — scarcity is fine when real
M|framing-analysis|- Never issue corrections that are vague ("consider more balanced framing") — provide the exact reframe